\begin_layout Subsection
Signal to noise ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The signal to noise ratio (SNR) is a physical quantity of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\text{SNR}=\frac{\left\langle i\right\rangle ^{2}}{\sigma_{i}},\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle i\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are, respectively, the mean and the variance of the current 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Physically, the definition tell how great is the information 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle i\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 compared to the mean fluctuations amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 due to noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Noise sources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The noise shown here in the detection band used can be considered white
 noise with zero mean and non correlated.
 The outcome of that is that the variance of the noise signals sum is equal
 to the sum of the variance of each noise signal.
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{i}=\sum_{n}\sigma_{n}^{2}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shot noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noise due to the quantization of light and electric current.
 The quantity of photons arriving at the detector in a sampling interval
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is not constant, even if the power of the light source is.
 The distribuition of the number of photons hitting the detector as a poissonian
 lineshape, whose width is equal to the mean number of photons.
 In addition to that, the photoelectron generation ocurs with a probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, defined as quantum efficiency.
 It can be shown, that the photoelectron current has a variance
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{s}^{2}=e\left\langle i\right\rangle B,\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the electron charge and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the detection bandwith of the circuit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relative intensity noise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative intensity noise (RIN) are noise that grows linearly with the mean
 photo-current power.
 A few examples include the optical source power fluctuations.
 The noise spectral density can be model with a white noise over the band
 of interest.
 Therefore, the variance of this noise can be described as
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sigma_{RIN}^{2}=e\gamma\left\langle i\right\rangle ^{2}B,\]

\end_inset

 where the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is experimentally measured.
 In practice it is possible to remove this noise using a balanced detection
 system.
